The '''black mannikin''' ('''''Lonchura stygia''''') or '''black munia''', is a species of [[estrildid finch]] found in [[New Guinea]], from [[Mandum]] ([[Papua (Indonesian province)|Papua]], formerly known as Irian Jaya, [[Indonesia]]) to [[Lake Daviumbu]], [[Papua New Guinea]]. It is commonly found in flocks of maximum 20 birds, inhabiting [[savannas]], [[wetlands]], but sometimes they were also seen at rice crops.

==Threats==
This species is threatened by the destruction of [[reedbeds]] due to the introduction of [[rusa deer]] (''Cervus timorensis'').{{cn|date=September 2024}} They are also probably threatened by the encroachment of [[woodland]] on grasslands, due to increased numbers of livestock such as pigs. It is also adversely affected by the cage-bird trade.{{cn|date=September 2024}}

